PRIORITY 1 SIMPLE OPERATORS SOURCE/SINK

DB acess operators
 * scan over relation_heap, in parallel with all partitions, atmost max_concurrent scans at a time (root_page_id, tuple_pointer, tuple_with_mvcc_versions) -> tuple_pointer can alone uniquely identify it, but we need root_page_id to update/delete it, it will have 1-7 output modes
 * insert/update/delete into relation for sink operator
 * scan over relation_index (bplus_tree index), in parallel with all partitions, given start_scan_key, start_find_pos and stop_scan_key, stop_find_pos, decides scan direction on it's own, start and scan can be exclusive inclusive, outputs same 1-7 output modes based tuples, i.e. looks up heap tuples on it's own
 * index_nested_loop_join
 * index_nested_loop_semi_join
   * both joins take key_element_count as input, and the index to look up from

 * mvcc check is done for the output of every scan
 * filter check is done again for the output of index if it's key is possibly extended type

 * deletes taken care of by trash_cleaner task over that tuple, to be implemented later, also takes care of filling up the hint bits of mvcc headers

 * table_locks -> locks the table_id of the table for schema changes
 * tuple_locks -> lock root_page_id, page_id, tuple_index -> on update or delete, lock the older version, newer version is not even visible
 * key_locks -> hash key how ever big it is concatenate it with root_page_id and lock it

 * for auto_increment store a counter in the db_table object and increment it and return it
 * for unique constraint maintain a lock in lock_manager and hold lock on the 80-bit serialized hash value and then only check the unique btree index







